# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: crank-mechanism
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] Al-Zahrawi's principal work is the *Kitab al-Tasrif*, a thirty-volume encyclopedia of medical practices.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] The surgery chapter of this work was later translated into Latin, attaining popularity and becoming the standard textbook in Europe for the next five hundred years.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] Al-Zahrawi's pioneering contributions to the field of surgical procedures and instruments had an enormous impact in the East and West well into the modern period, where some of his discoveries are still applied in medicine to this day.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] He pioneered the use of catgut for internal stitches, and his surgical instruments are still used today to treat people.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] He was the first physician to identify the hereditary nature of haemophilia and describe an abdominal pregnancy, a subtype of ectopic pregnancy that in those days was a fatal affliction, and was first to discover the root cause of paralysis.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] He also developed surgical devices for Caesarean sections and cataract surgeries.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] Al-Zahrawi was born in the city of Azahara, 8 kilometers northwest of Cordoba, Andalusia.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] His birth date is not known for sure, however, scholars agree that he was born around 936, the year his birthplace city of Azahara was founded.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] The nisba (attributive title), *Al-Ansari*, in his name, suggests origin from the Medinian tribe of Al-Ansar, thus, tracing his ancestry back to Medina in the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] It is also where he studied, taught and practiced medicine and surgery until shortly before his death in about 1013, two years after the sacking of Azahara.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] Few details remain regarding his life, aside from his published work, due to the destruction of El-Zahra during later Castillian-Andalusian conflicts.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] His name first appears in the writings of Abu Muhammad bin Hazm (993–1064), who listed him among the greatest physicians of Moorish Spain.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] But we have the first detailed biography of al-Zahrawī from al-Ḥumaydī's *Jadhwat al-Muqtabis* (*On Andalusian Savants*), completed six decades after al-Zahrawi's death.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] Al-Zahrawi was a court physician to the Andalusian caliph Al-Hakam II.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] He was a contemporary or near contemporary of Andalusian chemists such as Ibn al-Wafid, al-Majriti and Artephius.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] He devoted his entire life and genius to the advancement of medicine as a whole and surgery in particular.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] As a court physician, Zahrawi had access to the most advanced medical knowledge and resources of the time, allowing him to develop new techniques and instruments for surgical procedures.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] Zahrawi's time as a court physician to Al-Hakam II allowed him to develop his skills and knowledge as a physician and surgeon, and to make significant contributions to the field of medicine.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] His work helped to lay the foundation for modern surgical techniques and has had a lasting impact on the practice of medicine.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] Al-Zahrawi specialized in curing disease by cauterization.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] He invented several devices used during surgery, for purposes such as inspection of the interior of the urethra and also inspection, applying and removing foreign bodies from the throat, the ear and other body organs.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] He was also the first to illustrate the various cannulae and the first to treat a wart with an iron tube and caustic metal as a boring instrument.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] While al-Zahrawi never performed the surgical procedure of tracheotomy, he did treat a slave girl who had cut her own throat in a suicide attempt.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] Al-Zahrawi sewed up the wound and the girl recovered, thereby proving that an incision in the larynx could heal.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] Al-Zahrawi also pioneered neurosurgery and neurological diagnosis.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] He is known to have performed surgical treatments of head injuries, skull fractures, spinal injuries, hydrocephalus, subdural effusions and headache.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] The first clinical description of an operative procedure for hydrocephalus was given by Al-Zahrawi who clearly describes the evacuation of superficial intracranial fluid in hydrocephalic children.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] Al-Zahrawi's thirty-volume medical encyclopedia, *Kitāb al-Taṣrīf*, completed in the year 1000, covered a broad range of medical topics, including on surgery, medicine, orthopaedics, ophthalmology, pharmacology, nutrition, dentistry, childbirth, and pathology.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] The first volume in the encyclopedia is concerned with general principles of medicine, the second with pathology, while much of the rest discuss topics regarding pharmacology and drugs.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] The last treatise and the most celebrated one is about surgery.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] Al-Zahrawi stated that he chose to discuss surgery in the last volume because surgery is the highest form of medicine, and one must not practice it until he becomes well-acquainted with all other branches of medicine.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] The work contained data that had accumulated during a career that spanned almost 50 years of training, teaching and practice.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] In it he also wrote of the importance of a positive doctor–patient relationship and wrote affectionately of his students, whom he referred to as "my children".
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] He also emphasized the importance of treating patients irrespective of their social status.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] He encouraged the close observation of individual cases in order to make the most accurate diagnosis and the best possible treatment.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] Not always properly credited, modern evaluation of *Kitab al-Tasrif* manuscript has revealed on early descriptions of some medical procedures that were ascribed to later physicians.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] For example, Al-Zahrawi's *Kitab al-Tasrif* described both what would later become known as "Kocher's method" for treating a dislocated shoulder and "Walcher position" in obstetrics.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] Moreover, the *Kitab al-Tasrif* described how to ligature blood vessels almost 600 years before Ambroise Paré, and was the first recorded book to explain the hereditary nature of haemophilia.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] It was also the first to describe a surgical procedure for ligating the temporal artery for migraine, also almost 600 years before Pare recorded that he had ligated his own temporal artery for headache that conforms to current descriptions of migraine.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] Al-Zahrawi was, therefore, the first to describe the migraine surgery procedure that is enjoying a revival in the 21st century, spearheaded by Elliot Shevel, a South African surgeon.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] The book was translated into Latin in the 12th century by Gerard of Cremona.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] It soon found popularity in Europe and became a standard text in all major Medical universities like those of Salerno and Montpellier.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] It remained the primary source on surgery in Europe for the next 500 years, and as the historian of medicine, Arturo Castiglioni, has put it: al-Zahrawi's treatise "in surgery held the same authority as did the Canon of Avicenna in medicine".
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] Then through the whole of my life I have adhered to experience and practice...
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] I have made it accessible for you and rescued it from the abyss of prolixity".
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] In the beginning of his book, al-Zahrawi states that the reason for writing this treatise was the degree of underdevelopment surgery had reached in the Islamic world, and the low status it held amongst physicians at the time.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] Al-Zahrawi ascribed such decline to a lack of anatomical knowledge and a misunderstanding of the human physiology.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] In urology, al-Zahrawi wrote about taking stones out of the bladder.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] By inventing a new instrument, an early form of the lithotrite which he called michaab, he was able to crush the stone inside the bladder without the need for a surgical incision.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] His technique was important for the development of lithotomy, and an improvement over the existing techniques in Europe which caused severe pain for the patient, and came with high death rates.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] In dentistry and periodontics, al-Zahrawi had the most significant contribution out of all Muslim physicians, and his book contained the earliest illustrations of dental instruments.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] He was known to use gold and silver wires to ligate loosened teeth, and has been credited as the first to use replantation in the history of dentistry.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] He also invented instruments to scale the calculus from the teeth, a procedure he recommended as a prevention from periodontal disease.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] Al-Zahrawi introduced over 200 surgical instruments, which include, among others, different kinds of scalpels, retractors, curettes, pincers, specula, and also instruments designed for his favoured techniques of cauterization and ligature.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] He also invented hooks with a double tip for use in surgery.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] Many of these instruments were never used before by any previous surgeons.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] His use of catgut for internal stitching is still practised in modern surgery.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] Catgut appears to be the only natural substance capable of dissolving and is acceptable by the body, an observation Al-Zahrawi discovered after his monkey ate the strings of his oud.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] Al-Zahrawi also invented the forceps for extracting a dead fetus, as illustrated in the *Kitab al-Tasrif*.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] Throughout the text, Al-Zahrawi assumes an authoritative tone.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] In "On cauterization for numbness", he declares the procedure "should not be attempted except by one who has a good knowledge of the anatomy of the limbs and of the exits of the nerves that move the body".
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] He warns that another procedure should not be attempted by any surgeon lacking "long training and practice in the use of cautery".
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] He is not afraid to depart from old practice, disparaging the opinions that cauterization should only be used in the spring or that gold is the best material for cauterization: "cauterization is swifter and more successful with iron".
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] In "On cauterization for pleurisy", he notes that the introduction of a red-hot probe into the intercostal space to evacuate pus from an abscess could result in the creation of "an incurable fistula" or even the immediate death of the patient.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] In pharmacy and pharmacology, Al-Zahrawi pioneered the preparation of medicines by sublimation and distillation.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] He dedicated the 28th chapter of his book to pharmacy and pharmaceutical techniques.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] The chapter was later translated into Latin under the title of *Liber Servitoris*, where it served as an important source for European herbalists.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] The book is of particular interest, as it provides the reader with recipes and explains how to prepare the "simples" from which were compounded the complex drugs then generally used.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] Al-Zahrawi also touched upon the subject of cosmetics and dedicated a chapter for it in his medical encyclopedia.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] As the treatise was translated into Latin, the cosmetic chapter was used in the West.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] Al-Zahrawi considered cosmetics a branch of medicine, which he called "Medicine of Beauty" (*Adwiyat al-Zinah*).
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] He deals with perfumes, scented aromatics and incense.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] He also invented perfumed sticks rolled and pressed in special molds, perhaps the earliest antecedents of present-day lipsticks, and solid deodorants.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] Al-Zahrawi was the "most frequently cited surgical authority of the Middle Ages".
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] In the 14th century, the French surgeon Guy de Chauliac quoted *al-Tasrif* over 200 times.
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] 1453) described Al-Zahrawi as "without doubt the chief of all surgeons".
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] Al-Zahrawi's influence continued for at least five centuries, extending into the Renaissance, evidenced by *al-Tasrif'*s frequent reference by French surgeon Jacques Daléchamps (1513–1588).
[src:crank-mechanism/abu-al-qasim-al-zahrawi] The street in Córdoba where he lived is named in his honor as "Calle Albucasis".
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] Steam power has generally been superseded by the internal combustion engine or by electrical power drawn from an electrical grid.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] The only steam installations that are in widespread use are the highly efficient thermal power plants used for generating electricity on a large scale.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] In contrast, the proposed steam engines may be for stationary, road, rail, or marine use.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] Although most references to "Modern Steam" apply to developments since the 1970s, certain aspects of advanced steam technology can be discerned throughout the 20th century, notably automatic boiler control along with rapid startup.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] In 1922, Abner Doble developed an electro-mechanical system that reacted simultaneously to steam temperature and pressure, starting and stopping the feed pumps whilst igniting and cutting out the burner according to boiler pressure.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] The contraflow monotube boiler had a working pressure of 750–1,200 psi (5.17–8.27 MPa) but contained so little water in circulation as to present no risk of explosion.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] This type of boiler was continuously developed in the US, Britain and Germany throughout the 1930s and into the 1950s for use in cars, buses, trucks, railcars, shunting locomotives (US; switchers), a speedboat and, in 1933, a converted Travel Air 2000 biplane.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] In the UK, Sentinel Waggon Works developed a vertical water-tube boiler running at 275 psi (1.90 MPa) which was used in road vehicles, shunting locomotives and railcars.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] Steam could be raised much more quickly than with a conventional locomotive boiler.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] Trials of the Anderson condensing system took place on Britain's Southern Railway between 1930 and 1935.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] The Anderson condensing system uses a process known as mechanical vapor recompression.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] It was devised by a Glasgow marine engineer, Harry Percival Harvey Anderson.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] The theory was that, by removing around 600 of the 970 British thermal units present in each pound of steam (1400 of the 2260 kilojoules in each kilogram), it would be possible to return the exhaust steam to the boiler by a pump which would consume only 1–2% of the engine's power output.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] Between 1925 and 1927 Anderson, and another Glasgow engineer John McCullum (some sources give McCallum), conducted experiments on a stationary steam plant with encouraging results.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] A company, Steam Heat Conservation (SHC), was formed and a demonstration of Anderson's system was arranged at Surbiton Electricity Generating Station.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] SHC was interested in applying the system to a railway locomotive and contacted Richard Maunsell of the Southern Railway.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] Maunsell requested that a controlled test be carried out at Surbiton and this was done about 1929.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] Maunsell's technical assistant, Harold Holcroft, was present and a fuel saving of 29% was recorded, compared to conventional atmospheric working.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] The Southern Railway converted SECR N class locomotive number A816 (later 1816 and 31816) to the Anderson system in 1930.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] The locomotive underwent trials and initial results were encouraging.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] The trials continued until 1934 but various problems arose, mostly with the fan for forced draught, and the project went no further.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] The locomotive was converted back to standard form in 1935.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] The work of French mechanical engineer André Chapelon in applying scientific analysis and a strive for thermal efficiency was an early example of advanced steam technology.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] Chapelon's protégé Livio Dante Porta continued Chapelon's work.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] Postwar in the late 1940s and 1950s some designers worked on modernising steam locomotives.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] The Argentinian engineer Livio Dante Porta in the development of Stephensonian railway locomotives incorporating advanced steam technology was a precursor of the 'Modern Steam' movement from 1948.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] Where possible, Porta much preferred to design new locomotives, but more often in practice he was forced to radically update old ones to incorporate the new technology.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] 1949 by Oliver Bulleid and the British Rail ‘Standard’ class steam locomotives of the 1950s by Robert Riddles, particularly the BR Standard Class 9F, were used to trial new steam locomotive design features, including the Franco-Crosti boiler.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] On moving to Ireland, Bulleid also designed CIÉ No.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] The Sir Biscoe Tritton Lecture, given by Roger Waller, of the DLM company to the Institute of Mechanical Engineers in 2003 gives an idea of how problems in steam power are being addressed.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] Waller refers mainly to some rack and pinion mountain railway locomotives that were newly built from 1992 to 1998.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] They were developed for three companies in Switzerland and Austria and continued to work on two of these lines as of 2008.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] The new steam locomotives burn the same grade of light oil as their diesel counterparts, and all demonstrate the same advantages of ready availability and reduced labour cost; at the same time, they have been shown to greatly reduce air and ground pollution.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] Their economic superiority has meant that they have largely replaced the diesel locomotives and railcars previously operating the line; additionally, steam locomotives are a tourist attraction.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] A parallel line of development was the return to steam power of the old Lake Geneva paddle steamer *Montreux* that had been refitted with a diesel-electric engine in the 1960s.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] Economic aims similar to those achieved with the rack locomotives were pursued through automatic control of the light-oil-fired boiler and remote control of the engine from the bridge, enabling the steamship to be operated by a crew of the same size as a motor ship.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] A power unit based on advanced steam technology burning fossil fuel will inevitably emit carbon dioxide, a long-lasting greenhouse gas.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] However, significant reductions of other pollutants such as CO and NOx are achievable by steam compared to other combustion technologies, since it does not involve explosive combustion, thus removing the need for add-ons (such as filters) or special preparation of fuel.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] If renewable fuel such as wood or other biofuel is used then the system could be carbon neutral.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] The use of biofuel remains controversial; however, liquid biofuels are easier to manufacture for steam plant than for diesels as they do not demand the stringent fuel standards required to protect diesel injectors.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] In principle, combustion and power delivery of steam plant can be considered separate stages.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] High overall thermal efficiency may be difficult to achieve, largely due to the extra stage of generating a working fluid between combustion and power delivery attributable mainly to leakages and heat losses.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] The separation of the processes allows specific problems to be addressed at each stage without revising the whole system every time.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] For instance, the boiler or steam generator can be adapted to use any heat source, whether obtained from solid, liquid or gaseous fuel, and can use waste heat.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] Whatever the choice, it will have no direct effect on the design of the engine unit, as that only ever has to deal with steam.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] This project mainly includes combined electrical generation and heating systems for private homes and small villages burning wood or bamboo chips.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] This is intended to replace 2-stroke donkey engines and small diesel power plants.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] Drastic reduction in noise level is one immediate benefit of a steam-powered small plant.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] Ted Pritchard, of Melbourne, Australia, was intensively developing this type of unit from 2002 until his death in 2007.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] The company Pritchard Power (now Uniflow Power) stated in 2010 that they continue to develop the stationary S5000, and that a prototype had been built and was being tested, and designs were being refined for market ready products.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] Until 2006 a German company called *Enginion* was actively developing a *Steamcell*, a micro CHP unit about the size of a PC tower for domestic use.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] It seems that by 2008 it had merged with Berlin company AMOVIS.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] Since 2012, a French company, EXOES, is selling to industrial firms a Rankine Cycle, patented, engine, which is designed to work with many fuels such as concentrated solar power, biomass, or fossil.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] The system, called "SHAPE" for Sustainable Heat And Power Engine, converts the heat into electricity.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] The SHAPE engine is suitable for embedded, and stationary, applications.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] A SHAPE engine has been integrated into a biomass boiler, and into a Concentrated solar power system.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] The company is planning to work with automobile manufactures, long-haul truck manufactures, and railway corporations.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] A similar unit is marketed by Powertherm, a subsidiary of Spilling (see below).
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] A company in India manufactures steam-powered generators in a range of sizes from 4 hp to 50 hp.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] They also offer a number of different mills that can be powered by their engines.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] In matter of technology, notice that the Quasiturbine is a uniflow rotary steam engine where steam intakes in hot areas, while exhausting in cold areas.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] The Spilling company produces a variety of small fixed stationary plant adapted to biomass combustion or power derived from waste heat or pressure recovery.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] The Finnish company Steammotor Finland has developed a small rotary steam engine that runs with 800 kW steam generator.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] The engines are planned to produce electricity in wood chip fired power plants.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] According to the company, the steam engine named *Quadrum* generates 27% efficiency and runs with 180 °C steam at 8 bar pressure, while a corresponding steam turbine produces just 15% efficiency, requires steam temperature of 240 °C and pressure of 40 bar.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] The high efficiency comes from a patented crank mechanism, that gives a smooth, pulseless torque.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] The company believes that by further developing the construction there is potential to reach as high efficiency as 30–35%.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] During the first 1970s oil crisis, a number of investigations into steam technology were initiated by large automobile corporations although as the crisis died down, impetus was soon lost.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] Australian engineer Ted Pritchard's main field of research from the late 1950s until the 1970s was the building of several efficient steam power units working on the uniflow system adapted to a small truck and two cars.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] One of the cars was achieving the lowest emissions figures of that time.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] All these engines made heavy use of flameless ceramic heat cells both for the steam generator and at strategic boost points where steam was injected into the cylinder(s).
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] A design mounted on power bogies with compact water-tube boiler similar to Sentinel designs of the 1930s.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] Example: Sentinel-Cammell locomotive (right).
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] Both 52 8055 and the proposed 5AT are of conventional layout, with the cab at the back, while the ACE 3000 had the cab located at the front.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] Other approaches are possible, especially with liquid fuel firing.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] This is a well-tried design with the potential for a large power output and would provide the driver good visibility.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] Another well-tried design with large power potential.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] A future design could include shorter water tanks, and a cab at each end, to give the driver a good view in either direction.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] Another proposal for advanced steam technology is to revive the fireless locomotive, which runs on stored steam independently pre-generated.
[src:crank-mechanism/advanced-steam-technology] An example is the Solar Steam Train project in Sacramento, California.
[src:crank-mechanism/aeolipile] An **aeolipile**, **aeolipyle**, or **eolipile**, also known as a **Hero's** (or **Heron's**) **engine**, is a simple, bladeless radial steam turbine which spins when the central water container is heated.
[src:crank-mechanism/aeolipile] Torque is produced by steam jets exiting the turbine.
[src:crank-mechanism/aeolipile] The Greek-Egyptian mathematician and engineer Hero of Alexandria described the device in the 1st century CE, and many sources give him the credit for its invention.
[src:crank-mechanism/aeolipile] However, at least one source credits Vitruvius as the first to describe this appliance in his *De architectura* (c.
[src:crank-mechanism/aeolipile] The aeolipile is considered to be the first recorded steam engine or reaction steam turbine, but it is neither a practical source of power nor a direct predecessor of the type of steam engine invented during the Industrial Revolution.
[src:crank-mechanism/aeolipile] The name – derived from the Ancient Greek name Αἴολος and the Latin word *pila* – translates literally to 'the ball of Aeolus', Aeolus being the Greek god of the air and wind.
[src:crank-mechanism/aeolipile] Because it applies steam to perform work, an aeolipile (depicted in profile) is used as the symbol for the U.S.
[src:crank-mechanism/aeolipile] Navy's Boiler Technician Rate, as it was for the earlier Watertender, Boilermaker, and Boilerman ratings.
[src:crank-mechanism/aeolipile] The aeolipile usually consists of a spherical or cylindrical vessel with oppositely bent or curved nozzles projecting outwards.
[src:crank-mechanism/aeolipile] When the vessel is pressurised with steam, the gas is expelled out of the nozzles, which generates thrust due to the rocket principle as a consequence of the 2nd and 3rd of Newton's laws of motion.
[src:crank-mechanism/aeolipile] When the nozzles, pointing in different directions, produce forces along different lines of action perpendicular to the axis of the bearings, the thrusts combine to result in a rotational moment (mechanical couple), or torque, causing the vessel to spin about its axis.
[src:crank-mechanism/aeolipile] Aerodynamic drag and frictional forces in the bearings build up quickly with increasing rotational speed (rpm) and consume the accelerating torque, eventually cancelling it and achieving a steady state speed.
[src:crank-mechanism/aeolipile] Typically, and as Hero described the device, the water is heated in a simple boiler which forms part of a stand for the rotating vessel.
[src:crank-mechanism/aeolipile] Where this is the case, the boiler is connected to the rotating chamber by a pair of pipes that also serve as the pivots for the chamber.
[src:crank-mechanism/aeolipile] Alternatively the rotating chamber may itself serve as the boiler, and this arrangement greatly simplifies the pivot/bearing arrangements, as they then do not need to pass steam.
[src:crank-mechanism/aeolipile] This can be seen in the illustration of a classroom model shown here.
[src:crank-mechanism/aeolipile] Both Hero and Vitruvius draw on the much earlier work by Ctesibius (285–222 BCE), also known as Ktēsíbios or Tesibius, who was an inventor and mathematician in Alexandria, Ptolemaic Egypt.
[src:crank-mechanism/aeolipile] He wrote the first known treatises on the science of compressed air and its uses in pumps.
[src:crank-mechanism/aeolipile] It is not known whether the aeolipile was put to any practical use in ancient times, and if it was seen as a pragmatic device, a whimsical novelty, an object of reverence, or some other thing.
[src:crank-mechanism/aeolipile] A source described it as a mere curiosity for the ancient Greeks, or a "party trick".
[src:crank-mechanism/aeolipile] Hero's drawing shows a standalone device, and was presumably intended as a "temple wonder", like many of the other devices described in *Pneumatica*.
[src:crank-mechanism/aeolipile] Vitruvius, on the other hand, mentions use of the aeolipile for demonstrating the physical properties of the weather.
[src:crank-mechanism/aeolipile] This account was preserved by the royal Spanish archives at Simancas.
[src:crank-mechanism/aeolipile] It is proposed that de Garay used Hero's aeolipile and combined it with the technology used in Roman boats and late medieval galleys.
[src:crank-mechanism/aeolipile] Here, de Garay's invention introduced an innovation where the aeolipile had practical usage, which was to generate motion to the paddlewheels, demonstrating the feasibility of steam-driven boats.
[src:crank-mechanism/aeolipile] This claim was denied by Spanish authorities.
[src:crank-mechanism/agostino-ramelli] Ramelli was born in Ponte Tresa or Mesanzena, today in Switzerland.
[src:crank-mechanism/agostino-ramelli] During the Siege of La Rochelle (1572–1573), he successfully engineered a mine under a bastion and breached the fortification, making him popular with his commander, Henri d'Anjou, who later became King Henri III of France.
[src:crank-mechanism/agostino-ramelli] In 1588, Ramelli published *Le diverse et artificiose machine del Capitano Agostino Ramelli*, or *The various and ingenious machines of Captain Agostino Ramelli*.
[src:crank-mechanism/agostino-ramelli] The book contains 195 designs, over 100 of which are water-raising machines, such as water pumps or wells.
[src:crank-mechanism/agostino-ramelli] Other designs include bridges, mills, and a possible forerunner to the Wankel engine.
[src:crank-mechanism/agostino-ramelli] Some of his pump mechanisms feature early rotary and multi-piston concepts that conceptually resemble modern axial piston pumps (for example, those used today in car air conditioning compressors).
[src:crank-mechanism/agostino-ramelli] The bookwheel is one of the most famous designs from this book.
[src:crank-mechanism/agostino-ramelli] *Le diverse et artificiose machine* is still printed and sold.
[src:crank-mechanism/air-cooling] In all cases, the air has to be cooler than the object or surface from which it is expected to remove heat.
[src:crank-mechanism/air-cooling] This is due to the second law of thermodynamics, which states that heat will only move spontaneously from a hot reservoir (the heat sink) to a cold reservoir (the air).
[src:crank-mechanism/air-cooling] When operating in an environment with lower air pressure like high altitude or airplane cabins, the cooling capacity has to be derated compared to that of sea level.
[src:crank-mechanism/air-cooling] A rule-of-thumb formula to note: 1 – (h/17500) = derating factor.
[src:crank-mechanism/air-cooling] Where *h* is the height over sea level in meters.
[src:crank-mechanism/air-cooling] And the result is the factor that should be multiplied with the cooling capacity in [W] to get the cooling capacity at the specified height over sea level.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] A **crank** is an arm attached at a right angle to a rotating shaft by which circular motion is imparted to or received from the shaft.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] When combined with a connecting rod, it can be used to convert circular motion into reciprocating motion, or vice versa.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] The arm may be a bent portion of the shaft, or a separate arm or disk attached to it.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] Attached to the end of the crank by a pivot is a rod, usually called a connecting rod (conrod).
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] The term often refers to a human-powered crank which is used to manually turn an axle, as in a bicycle crankset or a brace and bit drill.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] In this case a person's arm or leg serves as the connecting rod, applying reciprocating force to the crank.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] There is usually a bar perpendicular to the other end of the arm, often with a freely rotatable handle or pedal attached.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] Almost all reciprocating engines use cranks (with connecting rods) to transform the back-and-forth motion of the pistons into rotary motion.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] The cranks are incorporated into a crankshaft.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] The Chinese used the crank-and-connecting rod in ancient blasting apparatus, textile machinery and agricultural machinery no later than the Western Han dynasty (202 BC – 9 AD).
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] It was first used in the manually operated quern and *long* (grain decortication item) before evolving into other devices.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] Qingjun, the hand-crank of the rotary quern was different from a crank, which was the combination of a hand-crank and a push-and-pull connecting rod by a hinge.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] Eventually crank-and-connecting rods were used in the inter-conversion or rotary and reciprocating motion for other applications such as flour-sifting, treadle spinning wheels, water-powered furnace bellows, and silk-reeling machines.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] Ancient Egyptians had manual drills resembling a crank at the time of the Old Kingdom (2686–2181 BCE) and even a hieroglyph for the tool.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] However the Ancient Egyptian drill didn't operate as a true crank.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] Later evidence for the crank, combined with a connecting rod in a machine, appears in the Ancient Greek Hierapolis sawmill in Roman Asia from the 3rd century AD and two stone sawmills at Gerasa, Roman Syria, and Ephesus, Greek Ionia under Rome, (both 6th century AD).
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] On the pediment of the Hierapolis mill, a waterwheel fed by a mill race is shown powering via a gear train two frame saws which cut rectangular blocks by the way of some kind of connecting rods and, through mechanical necessity, cranks.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] The accompanying inscription is in Greek.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] The crank and connecting rod mechanisms of the other two archaeologically attested sawmills worked without a gear train.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] The crank appears in the mid-9th century in several of the hydraulic devices described by the Banū Mūsā brothers in their *Book of Ingenious Devices*.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] These devices, however, made only partial rotations and could not transmit much power, although only a small modification would have been required to convert it to a crankshaft.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] Al-Jazari (1136–1206) described a crank and connecting rod system in a rotating machine in two of his water-raising machines.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] His twin-cylinder pump incorporated a crankshaft.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] A crank is later also described in an early 15th-century Arabic manuscript of Hero of Alexandria's *Mechanics*.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] The first rotary hand mills, or rotary querns, appeared in Spain (600 BC – 500 BC), before they spread to the East.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] The handle near the outer edge of the rotary part makes the crank, a human arm powering the rotation would be the connecting rod.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] The Antikythera mechanism, dated to around 200 BC, used a crank as a part of its mechanism.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] The crank was used to manually setup the starting date for a prediction.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] A Roman iron crank of yet unknown purpose dating to the 2nd century AD was excavated in Augusta Raurica, Switzerland.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] The 82.5 cm (32 inches) long piece has fitted to one end a 15 cm (6 inches) long bronze handle, the other handle being lost.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] An true iron crank about 40 cm (16 inches) long was excavated, along with a pair of shattered mill-stones of 50 to 65 cm (20 to 26 inches) diameter and diverse iron items, in Aschheim, close to Munich.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] The crank-operated Roman mill is dated to the late 2nd century AD.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] However an often cited modern reconstruction of a bucket-chain pump driven by hand-cranked flywheels from the Nemi ships has been dismissed as "archaeological fantasy".
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] A rotary grindstone − the earliest representation of one − which is operated by a crank handle is shown in the Carolingian manuscript *Utrecht Psalter*; the pen drawing of around 830 goes back to a late antique original.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] A musical tract ascribed to the abbot Odo of Cluny (c.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] 878−942) describes a fretted stringed instrument which was sounded by a resined wheel turned with a crank; the device later appears in two 12th-century illuminated manuscripts.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] There are also two pictures of Fortuna cranking her wheel of destiny from this and the following century.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] The Benedictine monk Theophilus Presbyter (c.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] 1070−1125) described crank handles "used in the turning of casting cores".
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] The Italian physician Guido da Vigevano (c.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] 1280−1349), planning for a new crusade, made illustrations for a paddle boat and war carriages that were propelled by manually turned compound cranks and gear wheels (center of image).
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] Medieval cranes were occasionally powered by cranks, although more often by windlasses.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] The crank became common in Europe by the early 15th century, often seen in the works of those such as the German military engineer Konrad Kyeser.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] Devices depicted in Kyeser's *Bellifortis* include cranked windlasses (instead of spoke-wheels) for spanning siege crossbows, cranked chain of buckets for water-lifting and cranks fitted to a wheel of bells.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] Kyeser also equipped the Archimedes screws for water-raising with a crank handle, an innovation which subsequently replaced the ancient practice of working the pipe by treading.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] The earliest evidence for the fitting of a well-hoist with cranks is found in a miniature of c.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] 1425 in the German *Hausbuch of the Mendel Foundation*.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] The first depictions of the compound crank in the carpenter's brace appear between 1420 and 1430 in various northern European artwork.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] One of the drawings of the Anonymous of the Hussite Wars shows a boat with a pair of paddle-wheels at each end turned by men operating compound cranks (see above).
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] The concept was much improved by the Italian engineer and writer Roberto Valturio in 1463, who devised a boat with five sets, where the parallel cranks are all joined to a single power source by one connecting-rod, an idea also taken up by his compatriot Francesco di Giorgio.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] In Renaissance Italy, the earliest evidence of a compound crank and connecting-rod is found in the sketch books of Taccola, but the device is still mechanically misunderstood.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] A sound grasp of the crank motion involved demonstrates a little later Pisanello who painted a piston-pump driven by a water-wheel and operated by two simple cranks and two connecting-rods.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] The 15th century also saw the introduction of cranked rack-and-pinion devices, called cranequins, which were fitted to the crossbow's stock as a means of exerting even more force while spanning the missile weapon (see right).
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] In the textile industry, cranked reels for winding skeins of yarn were introduced.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] Around 1480, the early medieval rotary grindstone was improved with a treadle and crank mechanism.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] Cranks mounted on push-carts first appear in a German engraving of 1589.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] Cranks were formerly common on some machines in the early 20th century; for example almost all phonographs before the 1930s were powered by clockwork motors wound with cranks.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] Reciprocating piston engines use cranks to convert the linear piston motion into rotational motion.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] Internal combustion engines of early 20th century automobiles were usually started with hand cranks (known as *starting handles* in the UK), before electric starters came into general use.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] A **crank axle** is a crankshaft which also serves the purpose of an axle.
[src:crank-mechanism/crank-mechanism] It is used on steam locomotives with inside cylinders.
